#Paper系列 

## Example of Horseshoe vortex phenomena
1. junction of an aeroplane wing with the fuselage
2. bridge pier
3. telegraph pole surrounded by a snowdrift
# Abstract
1. Pressure distributions
2. variation of the horseshoe vortex position position
3. Using smoke flow visualization techniques
# 1. Introduction
1. cylinder produces pressure gradients in its vicinity.

2. The boundary layer on the wall upstream of the cylinder is in a region of ~={purple}adverse pressure gradient] --> three-dimensional separation=~

3. The separated boundary layer rolls up downstream of
	the separation line to form a system of vortices.  --> This vortex system is swept around the base of the cylinder and assumes a ~={purple}characteristic shape=~ which has led to its name - the horseshoe vortex.
	1. figure 1 ~={purple}taken by E. P. Sutton and printed in Thwaites (1960)=~
		![[Paper系列/Baker, C. J. (1979). The laminar horseshoe vortex. Journal of Fluid Mechanics, 95(02), 347-367./Figure 1..png]]
4. A horseshoe vortex system will ~={purple}produce high wall shear stresses beneath it=~
	1. around a bridge pier in the sand bed of a river --> cause the bed to be eroded and a scour hole to form around the base of the obstacle.

5. ~={purple}Schwind (1962)=~
	1. a) regime 1：type flow only a very weak, slowly rotating vortex is formed
		![[a) regime1.png]]
	2. b) regime 2：single steady clockwise
		rotating vortex and a small triangular-shaped counter-rotating vortex visible
		![[b) regime2.png]]

	3. c) regime 3：The need for velocity gradients to be continuous implies that a second vortex rotating in the same direction as the main vortex must be present upstream of the small counter rotating vortex
		![[c) regime3.png]]
	4.  d&e) regime 4&5：regular oscillatory motion was observed with the main vortex apparently becoming isolated from the rest of the vortex system and moving towards the wedge, then moving back upstream.
		![[d) regime4.png]]
		![[e) regime5.png]]
# 2. Dimensional analysis
1. Symbols
	1. "$x_{v}$" is the distance from the obstacle centre to the centre of the vortex core on the plane of symmetry
	2. "$D$" is the obstacle diameter
	3. "$l$" is the obstacle height
	4. "$U$" is the freestream fluid velocity
	5. "$\delta^{*}$" is the boundary-layer displacement thickness
	6. "$H$" is the form parameter at the obstacle position when the obstacle is not in position.
	7. "$u^{'}_{y}$" is the distribution of turbulence with the oncoming boundary layer
	8. "$\mu$" is the fluid viscosity
	9. "$\rho$" is the fluid density
	10. "$x_{s}$" is the distance from the obstacle centre to the separation line upstream of the obstacle on the plane of symmetry
# 3. Experimental apparatus
1.  a) Flow visualization：carried out in a Smoke tunnnel, cylinder was  mounted on a plate on the centre-line of the tunnel working section
	1. The values of the non-dimensional variables quoted for tests in this tunnel should only be regarded as approximate because of ~={purple}wall interference effectes.=~
2.  b) Pressure measurement：It can be seen that the form parameter H is approximately equal to the value for boundary-layer growth on a flat plate in zero pressure gradient.
3.  c) Measurements of vortex oscillations：DISA hot-wire ‘u’ probes were inserted through a small hole in the wind tunnel wall beneath the horseshoe vortex system, so that the tips of the probes just extended into the flow.
4.  d) Velocity measurements：A frame-by-frame analysis of the films was then carried out and, by measuring the difference in position of the ends of the smoke filament between successive frames, the flow velocity within nearly all the regions of the vortex system could be determined.
# 4. Flow visualization results
### 4.1 Gerneral description of horseshoe vortex flows
1. The exact number of vortices was seen to depend upon the flow speed and cylinder size, more vortices appearing as the
speed increased
2.  above a certain flow speed the entire horseshoe vortex system began to oscillate in a regular manner with the two largest clockwise rotating vortices moving towards one another and apart again.
3. at higher speeds the largest clockwise rotating vortex ceased to be fed by smoke during part of the oscillation period and seemed to become detached from the rest of the vortex system.
4. at still higher speeds the flow appeared to he very unsteady and turbulent and showed no traces of periodicity
### 4.2 Detailed description of steady horseshoe vortices
