# 6. Variation of the horseshoe vortex position
1. As $UD/v < 5000$ increases, $x_{v}/D$ increases and, as $D/\delta^{*}$ increases, $x_{v}/D$ decreases.
		![[Figure 12..png]]

# 7. The oscillatory behaviour of horseshoe vortex systems
1. At any one speed four different waveforms could be seen at different times:
	1. a) a steady trace with no oscillations
	2. b) a low frequency oscillation $(St = fD/U = 0.26)$
	3. c) a high frequency oscillation ($St = 0.4$, increasing to about $0.6$ at higher $UD/\nu$)
	4. d) an irregular turbulent trace
2. The spectra obtained are shown in figures 13(a) and 13(b). 
		![[Figure 13..png]]
3. 
		![[Figure 14..png]]

4. Also it can be seen from figure15(a) that the Strouhal number for ~={purple}the wake vortex shedding of the cylinder is approximately 0.16 at all tunnel speeds, which bears no relationship to the observed frequencies of oscillation of the horseshoe vortex systems.=~Thus it appears that one can eliminate wake vortex shedding as a possible cause of the oscillations.		![[Figure 15..png]]
# 8. Velocity measurements in the smoke tunnel
1. Velocity proliles and their positions.
	1. Radial flow component was mesured in two ways
		a) resolving the flow velocity at the measursment sections in a radial direction.
		b) measuring the variation of the distance of a streamline from the vortex centre between two successive crossings by the streamline of the measurement section.	
		c) The latter method effectively gives mean radial velocity for half a streamline spiral around the vortex. However, these methods gave more or less identical results close to the centre of the vortices.		
		![[Figure 16.(a).png]]
		![[Figure 16.(b).png]]
2. Figure 17 shows that the non-dimensional velocity profiles do not vary greatly in and beneath the vortex core. 
		![[Figure 17..png]]
	1. as $UD/\nu$ increases vortex1 moves away from the cylinder to a position where the dimensionless velocity outside the vortex system is higher.
	2. 
3. Figure 18 the distribution of skin friction beneath the horseshoe vortex system is shown
		![[Figure 18..png]]
	3. The dotted lines in the figure indicate a region where the skin friction could not be measured.
	4. The most striking feature of this figure is the high value of $|C_{f}|$ beneath vortex1.
	5. Thus although over much of the vortex system on the $|C_{f}|$plane of symmetry there is a reduction in from its freestream value, there is a $|C_{f}|$ considerable increase in beneath vortex 1.
# 9. Conclusions
1. A) The horseshoe vortex upstream of a cylinder in a laminar boundary layer has been visualized using smoke flow visualization. Three different types of vortex system have been observed which are, with increasing $UD/\nu$ :
	1. a) Steady horseshoe vortex systems with 2,4 or 6 vortices, the number of vortices increasing as $UD/\nu$ increases;	
	2. b) regular oscillatory motion
	3. c) irregular unsteady behaviour
2. B) Pressure distributions were measured on the plane of symmetry upstream of models of various types over a wide range of flow conditions $(2000 < UD/v < 16 000, 20 < D/\delta^{*} < 70)$. Two types of pressure distribution were measured.
	1. a) Pressure distributions which show minima. Flow visualization shows that such minima are at the position of the horseshoe vortex. ~={purple}Thus the vortex position can be determined from such pressure distributions. =~
	2. b) Pressure distributions which show no minima. Flow visualization shows that this type of pressure distribution occurs when the horseshoe vortex systems are unsteady.
3. C) $|x_{v}/D|$ increases as $UD/\nu$ increases and as $D/\delta^{*}$ decreases
	1. the horseshoe vortex position is not solely determined by this separation position but some other effect plays a part
4. D) As the Reynolds number UD/v increased steady horseshoe vortex systems began to oscillate intermittently and randomly at two different frequencies.
	1. As $UD/\nu$ increased further the periods of oscillation became longer, the high frequency oscillation becoming more common.
	2. At yet higher $UD/\nu$ the oscillations became irregular and the horseshoe vortex system became turbulent.
	3. These oscillations are not caused by vortex shedding in the wake of the models or by any small disturbances within the wind tunnel. It is concluded that ~={purple} the frequency of these oscillations is solely determined by the values of $UD/\nu$ and $D/\delta^{*}$. =~
5. E) A radial flow component can be measured only in vortices1 and 2, and appears to increase linearly with the distance from the centre of the vortex, in the central region of the vortex
6. F) The skin friction coefficient beneath vortex 1 was found to have a numerical value of five times its value far upstream of the cylinder, for $UD/\nu = 2610, D/\delta^{*} = 14.8.$
